(% style=&amp;#34;line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)Plan

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== The United States federal government should remove requirements for multi-step, multi-agency licensing and remove the moratorium on licenses for small modular reactors. ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== 1AC Prolif ===

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Contention One: Prolif ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Global nuclear renaissance makes proliferation and weaponization likely without nuclear leadership ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Hamre and Sowcroft 2012**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (John Hamre, President and CEO, Center for Strategic and International Studies. Lieutenant General Brent Scowcroft (Ret.), Former National Security Advisor, CSIS Counselor and Trustee.)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(4/11/2012 “Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) Global Security Forum 2012 Scenario 2030: Is the U.S. Nuclear Industry Dying?” http:~/~/csis.org/event/global-security-forum-2012-scenario-2030-us-nuclear-industry-dying)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)MR. HAMRE: Well, Brent, the only place where the wind blows 100 percent of the time is Washington. So I mean, this is the only place you could substitute – (laughter) – nuclear for wind power.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)But let me take you – also, you’re wearing your national security hat – you know, but –

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Going back to Eisenhower, he was trying to find a framework where we would manage the danger of nuclear power but we would still allow its promise for the world. And what – but now we’re in this period where, look, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__America is going to shrink__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). I mean – just by very conservative forecast, 20 years from now (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__we’ll probably be down to 50 or 60 plants in America__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), and (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__the rest of the world is going to build__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ probably __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__200__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). So there’ll be about 600 plants in the world, 10 percent of them anyways. And if you go out another 20 years, it’s probably going to be 2 percent in the U.S. How does America shape the security environment if this trend continues? How do you think about that, as a former national security advisor?

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)GEN. SCOWCROFT: Well, I think about that a lot. And I didn’t even go to the national security aspects of it, which I think are dominant in a way. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__We’re going to have a nuclear world. We’re not doing anything__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) But Saudi Arabia, the homeland of petroleum, is building nuclear plants.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)MR. HAMRE: Nineteen.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)GEN. SCOWCROFT: Most of the world is building nuclear plants now – rapidly. We’re not. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__The national security aspect of nuclear weapons – of nuclear energy is also extremely importan__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)t.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)And (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__is there a way that we can spread nuclear power for its benefits and control the resulting capability to go to nuclear weapons__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__,__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) which is a world we’re trying to avoid right now. And that’s a difficult question, especially (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__if we are not in the nuclear power business; then we lose all of our ability to control the development of nuclear__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ energy __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__around the world__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) in a way (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__which provides the benefits of__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ nuclear energy __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__without the detriment of weaponization__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
MR. HAMRE: You know, if by 2050 we’re down to two nuclear power plants, it’s going to be hard to tell China with 150 how they ought to behave with nuclear power.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== The plan addresses prolif in two ways ====

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== First, strong nuclear industry: ====

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== The US nuclear industry is in decline – reviving it is key to set the global standard for nuclear expansion and restore nonproliferation credibility ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Wallace and Williams 12 **(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(Michael Wallace comes to CSIS from Constellation Energy, where he served as vice chairman and COO. During his nine years at Constellation Energy, he led many company business activities, including the formation and operation of two joint ventures with EDF related to nuclear energy. Prior to joining Constellation Energy, he was cofounder and managing director of Barrington Energy Partners, LLC, a strategic consulting firm specializing in energy industry transactions and advisory services. Sarah J. Williams is program coordinator and research associate in the U.S. Nuclear Energy Project at CSIS. Prior to joining CSIS, she was a Herbert Scoville Jr. peace fellow and program coordinator at the Center for Science, Technology and Security Policy at the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS).)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(4/17/12 “Nuclear Energy in America: Preventing its Early Demise” http:~/~/csis.org/files/publication/120417_gf_wallace_williams.pdf)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Meanwhile, China, India, Russia, and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__other countries are looking to significantly expand their nuclear energy__(%%) commitments. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__By 2016, China could have 50__ nuclear power __plants in operation__(%%), compared with only 14 in 2011. India could add 8 new plants and Russia 10 in the same time frame. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__These trends are expected to accelerate__(%%) out to 2030, by which time China, India, and Russia could account for nearly 40 percent of global nuclear generating capacity.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Meanwhile, several smaller nations, mostly in Asia and the Middle East, are planning to get into the nuclear energy business for the first time. In all, as many as 15 new nations could have this technology within the next two decades. Meanwhile, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__America’s share of__(%%) global (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__nuclear generation is expected to shrink__(%%), from about 25 percent today to about 14 percent in 2030, and—if current trends continue—to less than 10 percent by mid-century.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__With the center of gravity for__(%%) global (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__nuclear investment shifting__(%%) to a new set of players,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ the U__(%%)nited (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__S__(%%)__tates and the international community (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)face(%%)__ a difficult set of(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ challenges: stemming the spread of nuclear weapons-usable materials and know-how; __(%%)preventing further catastrophic nuclear accidents;(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ providing for safe__(%%), long-term nuclear (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__waste management__(%%); (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)and protecting U.S. energy security and economic competitiveness. In this c(%%)ontext, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__federal action to reverse the__(%%) American(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ nuclear industry’s impending decline is__(%%) a national security (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__imperative__(%%). The United States cannot afford to become irrelevant in a new nuclear age.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Our nation’s commercial nuclear industry, its military nuclear capabilities, and its strong regulatory institutions can be seen as three legs of a stool. All three legs are needed to support America’s future prosperity and security and to shape an international environment that is conducive to our long-term interests.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Three__(%%) specific(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ aspects of U.S. leadership are __(%%)particularly(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ important__(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
First, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__managing the__ national and __global security risks associated with the spread of nuclear tech__nology to countries that don’t necessarily share the same perspective on issues of nonproliferation and nuclear (%%)security or may lack the resources to implement effective safeguards in this area. An approach that relies on(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ influence__(%%) and involvement (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__through a viable domestic industry is likely to be more effective__(%%) and less expensive (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__than trying to contain these risks militarily__(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Second, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__setting global norms and standards for safety__(%%), security, operations, and emergency response. As the world learned with past nuclear accidents and more recently with Fukushima, a major accident anywhere can have lasting repercussions everywhere. As with nonproliferation and security, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__America’s ability to exert leadership and influence__ in this area __is directly linked to the strength of our domestic industry and__(%%) our (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__active involvement in the__(%%) global(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ nuclear enterprise. A strong domestic__(%%) civilian (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__industry__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__and regulatory structure__(%%) have immediate national security significance in that they help(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ support the nuclear capabilities __(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__of the U.S__(%%)__.__ Navy, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)national laboratories, __weapons complex__(%%), and research institutions.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Third, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__in the past, the __(%%)U.S. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__government could exert influence by striking __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__export __(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__agreements with countries whose__(%%) regulatory and legal (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__frameworks reflected__(%%) and were consistent with (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__our__(%%) own (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__nonproliferation standards__(%%) and commitments. At the same time, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__our nation__(%%) set the global standard for effective, independent safety regulation (in the form of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission), led international efforts to reduce proliferation risks (through the 1970 NPT Treaty and other initiatives), and provided a model for industry self-regulation.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
The results were not perfect, but (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__America’s__(%%) institutional(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ support__(%%) for global nonproliferation goals and the regulatory behaviors it (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)modeled __clearly helped shape the way nuclear tech__nology __was__(%%) adopted and(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ used __elsewhere __around the world. This influence seems certain to wane if the U__nited __S__tates __is no longer a major__(%%) supplier or __user__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__of nuclear tech__nology. __With existing nonproliferation__(%%) and safety and security (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__regimes looking increasingly inadequate__(%%) in this rapidly changing global nuclear landscape, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__American leadership and leverage is more important__(%%) and more central to our national security interests (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__than ever__(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
To maintain its leadership role in the development, design, and operation of a growing global nuclear energy infrastructure, the next administration, whether Democrat or Republican, must recognize the invaluable role played by the commercial U.S. nuclear industry and take action to prevent its early demise.

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Second, spread of SMRs: ====

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== SMRs eliminate the incentive for countries to develop nuclear enrichment knowledge and capacity. ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Ioannis (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Kessides**(%%), Chief Economist for the Development Research Group @ World Bank, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**and**(%%) Vladimir (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Kuznetsov**(%%), Consultant for the World Bank, July 20(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**12 **(%%)(“Small Modular Reactors for Enhancing Energy Security in Developing Countries.” http:~/~/www.mdpi.com/2071-1050/4/8/1806/htm)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
One of the key concerns regarding nuclear deployment in developing countries is that those countries generally have a less mature regulatory regime in place compared to the advanced industrial countries. These considerations place very stringent requirements on power station reliability and safety performance. The need for enhanced levels of safety can be more easily met by SMRs with design options that maximize the use of inherent and passive safety features and incorporate additional layers of “defense in depth” [13]. These safety features can be more easily and effectively implemented in SMRs because of these reactors’ larger surface-to-volume ratio, reduced core power density, lower source term, and less frequent (multi-year) refueling. For example, large surface-to-volume ratios facilitate the passive (with no external source of electrical power or stored energy) removal of decay heat. The extent to which nuclear power will prove an acceptable and enduring option for meeting the future energy requirements worldwide will depend in part upon the ability of the international community to minimize the associated proliferation risks. A major (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__nuclear expansion__(%%) program, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__unless__(%%) is (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__accompanied by__(%%) adequate (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__technical__(%%) and institutional (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__safeguards__(%%), (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__could __(%%)increase the risk that weapons-usable fissile materials, facilities, technology, or expertise might be diverted or stolen. The common fear is that such an expansion will(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ make it easier for countries to acquire technology as a precursor to developing nuclear weapons capability or for terrorist groups to obtain nuclear materials. This risk could be __(%%)further(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ compounded by __(%%)the likelihood that(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ plutonium-fueled breeder reactors__(%%) will be widely used to stretch uranium resources(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ under expanded nuclear power deployment__(%%). Enhanced capacity and institutional arrangements to prevent proliferation and diversion of nuclear technology to non-peaceful purposes are challenges that will need to be overcome if nuclear energy is to be expanded in developing countries (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__One__(%%) potential (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__way of __(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__mitigating the__(%%)__ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)prolif(%%)__eration (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__risks__(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__of expanded nuclear deployment__(%%) in developing countries (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__might be through__(%%) the adoption of hub-and-spoke configurations that restrict all sensitive activities (such as isotope separation of uranium or reprocessing of spent fuel) to large, international/regional energy parks that would export fuel, hydrogen, and even (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__small__(%%) (40–50 megawatts) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__sealed reactors__(%%) to client states [30,31]. These reactors would be assembled and fueled at the central nuclear park, sealed ((% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__so that individual fuel assemblies could not be removed__(%%)) and delivered as a unit to the power plant cites of client countries.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ At the end of their core life__(%%) (say 15–20 years) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__the reactors would be returned __(%%)to the central park(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ unopened__(%%). Thus, during the 15–20 years of operation(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ there would be no refueling and__(%%) consequently the (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__client countries would need no fuel fabrication facilities__(%%) and management capabilities.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__** To the extent that such modular reactors would operate almost autonomously, the hub-and-spoke architecture could reduce substantially the rationale and opportunities for countries to develop nuclear research laboratories and train**__(%%) technical specialists and(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__** scientists whose know-how could later be diverted to weapons activities**__(%%) [32]. It should be noted that providing attractive alternatives to the buildup of indigenous facilities is a good idea. However, trying to restrict knowledge diffusion is arguable futile and non-sustainable.

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== SMRs make covert efforts at prolif incredibly obvious – ensures international response. ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Harold (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Feiveson**(%%), Senior Research Policy Analyst @ Program on Science and Global Security at Princeton, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**et al.**(%%) Alexander Glaser, Asst Prof. at Woodrow Wilson School of Public Affairs @ Princeton, Marvin Miller, Senior Scientist Emeritus @ MIT Center for International Studies, and Lawrence Scheinman, International Policy @ Monterey Institute of International Studies, 200(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**8**(%%) (http:~/~/www.cissm.umd.edu/papers/files/future_nuclear_power.pdf)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)With respect to country proliferation:

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
• (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__Any country with__(%%) nuclear power and (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__a n__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__uclear power infrastructure could get fissile material__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ if it wished__(%%) – within months or a year – (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__barring international action__(%%) to prevent this. If it had a commercial reactor, it could build a reprocessing plant to separate out plutonium; or it could build a dedicated reactor and reprocessing plant in a somewhat longer period. It could also enrich uranium over time, but as long as the country did not have any enrichment facilities to begin with, such a route would take longer than would a plutonium path. • However, in the scenarios considered(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %), (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__it should be possible to have__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ a __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__safeguards regime such that any diversion__(%%) of facilities and materials(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__would be quickly detected, giving time for an international response__(%%) (see the following bullet). In this respect, the once-through fuel cycle, the hub-spoke arrangements with__ (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)sealed reactors(%%)__, and possibly certain thorium cycles (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__appear__(%%) particularly (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__attractive in making__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ immediately __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__visible an attempted diversion and lengthening the time for a diversion to be consummated__(%%). • Since technically most countries will be able to get nuclear weapons, enforcement and compliance provisions of any international control regime are crucial. • Compliance will be stronger and more accepted if nuclear power is nondiscriminatory. That is, for example, if countries such as the United States wish to have breeder reactors, it will be hard to argue that other countries should not be allowed these. • Secondly, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__compliance will be__(%%) surer and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__more effective if ventures to produce fissile material__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ for weapons __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__can quickly be seen and monitored__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ by__(%%) multinational or (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__international authorities __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__and if the acquisition of__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ significant quantities of __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__fissile material__(%%) by a country, clandestinely or overtly, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__will take__(%%) months or (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__longer__(%%). For this reason, we believe that all “sensitive” or “dangerous” nuclear facilities should ideally be put under multinational or international control. This includes reprocessing and enrichment plants. It might include also all uranium mining and milling and spent fuel. In time, the fuel could be “owned” by an international authority.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Times New Roman, serif;&amp;#34; %)International norms and response solve proliferation – empirics prove.(%%) ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Reed ’10**(%%), [Alexander R. Reed, Master of Arts in Security Studies from Georgetown University, April 14, 2010 “The Role of Denial in Nuclear Nonproliferation,” [[https:~~/~~/repository.library.georgetown.edu/bitstream/handle/10822/553565/reedAlexander.pdf?sequence=1&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:https://repository.library.georgetown.edu/bitstream/handle/10822/553565/reedAlexander.pdf?sequence=1]]]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__Incentives for integration with the international community benefitted nonproliferation¶ Incentives for normalization__(%%)__ also (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)played significant roles in(%%) some of the nonproliferation ¶ successes studied. (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)Libya, South Africa, and Brazi(%%)l (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)all sought increased integration(%%) ¶ within the international community, (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)but had to forgo their nuclear weapons programs(%%) ¶ before such integration could occur. __South Africa, long isolated due to its policy of(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)¶ (%%)apartheid, sought to establish a cooperative relationship with international (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)¶ (%%)community.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)¶ (%%)137(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:0.6em;&amp;#34; %)¶ (%%)While eliminating apartheid was the biggest step, __South Africa also had ¶ to renounce its nuclear weapons. The (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)sanctions and isolation imposed by the ¶ international community(%%)__ against apartheid thus (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__had a significant effect on South Africa__(%%)__’s ¶ nuclear weapons motivations. (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)Brazil(%%) similarly wanted to integrate into the international ¶ community. The Brazilian Government initially saw nuclear weapons as a means to ¶ increase its prestige among global powers.¶ 138¶ When the civilian government took ¶ control, however, it (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)saw nuclear weapons as an obstacle to unrestricted membership(%%) ¶ and leadership in the international community.¶ 139¶ (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)Brazil chose to renounce its weapons ¶ programs and alleviate international pressure(%%) to help accomplish that central goal.__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Prolif causes extinction. ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Heisbourg ’12**(%%), [Francois Heisbourg, Chairman of the International Institute for Strategic Studies, prof at the Geneva Center for Security Policy, July 2012, “How Bad Would the Further Spread of Nuclear Weapons Be?”, [[http:~~/~~/www.npolicy.org/userfiles/file/oving%20Beyond%20Pretense%20web%20version.pdf#page=182&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:#page=182]]]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Human societies__(%%) tend to (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__lack the imagination to think through__(%%), and to act upon, what have become known as (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__“black swan” events__(%%) 26 : (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__That which has never occurred__(%%) (or which has happened very rarely and in a wholly different context) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__is deemed not to be in the field of reality__(%%)__,__ and to which must be added eventualities that are denied because their consequences are too awful to contemplate. The extremes of human misconduct (the incredulity in the face of evidence of the Holocaust, the failure to imagine 9/11) bear testimony to this hardwired trait of our species. This would not normally warrant mention as a factor of growing salience if not for the recession into time of the original and only use of nuclear weapons in August 1945. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Nonuse of nuclear weapons may soon be taken for granted__(%%) rather than being an absolute taboo. Recent writing on the reputedly limited effects of the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombs 27 may contribute to such a trend, in the name of reducing the legitimacy of nuclear weapons. Recent, and often compelling, historical accounts of the surrender of the Japanese Empire that downplay the role of the atomic bombings in comparison to early research can produce a similar effect, even if that may not have been the intention. 28 However desirable it has been, the end of atmospheric nuclear testing 29 has removed for more than three decades the periodic reminders that such monstrous detonations made as to the uniquely destructive nature of nuclear weapons. There is a real and growing risk that we forget what was obvious to those who first described in 1941 the unique nature of yet-to-be produced nuclear weapons. 30 The risk is no doubt higher in those states for which the history of World War II has little relevance and that have not had the will or the opportunity to wrestle at the time or ex post facto with the moral and strategic implications of the nuclear bombing of Japan in 1945. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Unsustainable strains are__(%%) possibly (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__the single most compelling feature of contemporary proliferation__(%%)__.__ Examples include (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__tight geographical constraints__(%%)__–__with, for instance, New Delhi and Islamabad, located within 300 miles of each other; nuclear multi-polarity against the backdrop of multiple, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__crisscrossing sources of tension in the Middle East, as opposed to the relative simplicity of the U.S.-Soviet confrontation__(%%); the existence of (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__doctrines__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Times New Roman, serif;&amp;#34; %),(%%) such as India’s “cold start,” and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__force postures__(%%), such as Pakistan’s broadening array of battle- field nukes, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__that rest on the expectation of early use; and the role of non-state actors as aggravating or triggering factors when they are perceived as operating with the connivance of an antagonist state__(%%) (in the past, the assassination of the Austrian Archduke in Sarajevo in 1914; and in the future, Hezbollah operatives launching rockets with effect against Israel or Lashkar-e-Taiba commandos doing a “Bombay” redux in India?). (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Individually or in combination, these factors test crisis management capabilities more severely than anything__(%%) seen (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__during the Cold War__(%%) with the partial exception of the Cuban Missile Crisis. Even the overabundant battlefield nuclear arsenals in Cold War Central Europe, with their iffy weapons’ safety and security arrangements, were less of a challenge: The U.S. and Soviet short-range nuclear weapons so deployed were not putting U.S. and Soviet territory and capitals at risk. It may be argued that these risk factors are known to potential protagonists and that they therefore will be led to avoid the sort of nuclear brinksmanship that characterized U.S. and Soviet behavior during the Cold War in crises such as the Korean War, Berlin, Cuba or the Yom Kippur War. Unfortunately, the multiple nuclear crises between India and Pakistan demonstrate no such prudence, rather the contrary. And were such restraint to feed into nuclear policy and crisis planning, along the lines of apparently greater U.S. and Soviet nuclear caution from the mid-seventies onwards, the fact would remain that (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__initial intent rarely resists the strains of a complex, multiactor confrontation between inherently distrustful antagonists__(%%). It is also worth reflecting on the fact that during the 1980s there was real and acute fear in Soviet ruling circles that the West was preparing an out-of-the-blue nuclear strike, a fear which in turn fed into Soviet policies and dispositions. 31 (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__The Cold War was a set of crises and misunderstandings that came within a whisker of a nuclear holocaust. India and Pakistan’s nuclear ¶ standoff is deeply unstable, not least as a result of the interaction with non-state actors. A multipolar nuclear Middle East would make ¶ the Cuban Missile Crisis look easy in comparison__(%%)__.__

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== (% style=&amp;#34;font-family:Times New Roman, serif;&amp;#34; %)Proliferation causes nuclear deterrence to fail. Impossible to replicate Cold War stability.(%%) ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Shultz et al. ’11**(%%), George P. Shultz, former secretary of state, William J. Perry, former secretary of defense, Henry A. Kissinger, former secretary of state, and Sam Nunn, former chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, 04-07-2011“Deterrence in an Age of Nuclear Deterrence”, [[http:~~/~~/www.nonukes.nl/media/files/2011-03-07-gang-of-four-tnw.pdf&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://www.nonukes.nl/media/files/2011-03-07-gang-of-four-tnw.pdf]]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
__As long as there has been war, there have been efforts to deter__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) actions a nation considers(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)threatening. Until fairly recently, this meant building a military establishment capable of(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)intimidating the adversary, defeating him or making his victory more costly than the projected(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)gains. This, with conventional weapons, took time. Deterrence and war strategy were identical.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__The advent of the nuclear weapon introduced entirely new factors__(%%)__.__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) It was possible, for the first(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)time, to inflict at the beginning of a war the maximum casualties. The doctrine of mutual(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)assured destruction represented this reality. Deterrence based on nuclear weapons, therefore,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)has three elements:

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
 (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)It is importantly psychological, depending on calculations for which there is no historical(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)experience. It is therefore precarious.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
 (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)It is devastating. An unrestrained nuclear exchange between superpowers could destroy(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)civilized life as we know it in days.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
 __Mutual assured destruction raises enormous inhibitions against employing the weapons__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Since the first use of nuclear weapons against Japan, neither of the superpowers, nor any other(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)country, has used nuclear weapons in a war. A gap opened between the psychological element(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)of deterrence and the risks most leaders were willing to incur. U.S. defense leaders made(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)serious efforts to give the president more flexible options for nuclear use short of global(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)annihilation. They never solved the problem, and it was always recognized that Washington(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)and Moscow both held the keys to unpredictable and potentially catastrophic escalations.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
As a result, nuclear deterrence was useful in preventing only the most catastrophic scenarios¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)that would have threatened our survival. But (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__even with the deployment of thousands of nuclear¶ weapons__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) on both sides of the Iron Curtain, the (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__Soviet moves into Hungary in 1956 and¶ Czechoslovakia in 1968__(%%)__ were not deterred(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %). Nor were(%%) the numerous crises involving Berlin,¶ including the building of the Wall in 1961, or (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)major wars in Korea and Vietnam, or the Soviet¶ invasion of Afghanistan in 1979(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). In the case of the Soviet Union, nuclear weapons did not(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)prevent collapse or regime change.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Today, the Cold War is almost 20 years behind us, but many leaders and publics cannot(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)conceive of deterrence without a strategy of mutual assured destruction. We have written(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)previously (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__that reliance on this strategy is becoming increasingly hazardous. With the spread of¶ nuclear weapons, technology, materials and know__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Cambria Math serif; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__‐__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__how, there is an increasing risk that nuclear¶ weapons will be used__(%%)__.__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__It is not possible to replicate the high__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Cambria Math serif; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__‐__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__risk stability that prevailed between the two nuclear¶ superpowers__(%%)__ during the Cold War in such an environment. (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)The growing number of nations¶ with nuclear arms(%%) and differing motives, aims and ambitions (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)poses very high and¶ unpredictable risks and increased instability.(%%)__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
__From 1945 to 1991, America and the Soviet Union were diligent, professional, but also lucky¶ that nuclear weapons were never used. (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)Does the world want to continue to bet its survival on¶ continued good fortune(%%) with a growing number of nuclear nations and adversaries globally?¶__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Can we devise and successfully implement with other nations, including other nuclear powers,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)careful, cooperative concepts to safely dismount the nuclear tiger while strengthening the(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)capacity to assure our security and that of allies and other countries considered essential to our(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.6em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)national security?

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
&amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;_GoBack&amp;#34;/}}

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== 1AC Economy ===

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Contention Two is the economy ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Scenario one is manufacturing ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== We’re struggling out of a recession now – but manufacturing is slowing ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Reuters 12**

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(6/15/12 Dip in Manufacturing Suggests a Stalled U.S. Economy http:~/~/www.nytimes.com/2012/06/16/business/economy/dip-in-manufacturing-could-suggest-stalled-economy.html#h[TiaIau,2])

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)WASHINGTON (Reuters) — Factory output contracted in May for the second time in three months, the Federal Reserve said on Friday, and families took a dimmer view of their economic prospects in early June, signs that the economy’s recovery is on shaky ground.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ The new data was the latest in a series of reports portraying a weak economy that have led analysts to cut growth forecasts while raising expectations that the Federal Reserve will offer new stimulus measures.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Until recently, manufacturing had been a buttress for the __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__nation’s__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__economy, helping it resist headwinds from Europe’s__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ snowballing __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__debt crisis__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ But (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__in May, factory output shrank 0.4 percent__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), with plants producing fewer cars and less machinery, Federal Reserve data showed.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ “(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__It’s more convincing evidence that __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__the economy is stuck in low gear,__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__”__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) said Joe Manimbo, a market analyst at Travelex Global Business Payments.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ Other reports pointed to cooling factory activity in New York State this month, along with a drop in household confidence in the economy.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ The fall in confidence poses a serious threat to President Obama’s chances of winning re-election in November. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__It could also lead consumers to cut back on spending, which would reduce economic growth__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ “Consumers are scared,” said Sharon Stark, managing director at Sterne Agee in Birmingham, Ala.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ Consumer sentiment fell in early June to a six-month low. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__A gauge of household confidence in the economy’s future also dropped to its lowest__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) since December.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ The Thomson Reuters/University of Michigan’s index on consumer sentiment slipped to 74.1, falling short of even the most pessimistic forecast in a Reuters poll.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ Economists at Capital Economics reckon the decline in consumer sentiment is consistent with growth in consumer spending slowing to a mere 1 percent annual rate in the second quarter, down from 2.7 percent in the first three months of the year.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ The weakening recovery in the United States and a worsening debt crisis in Europe have bolstered expectations of a further easing of monetary policy by the Fed, although economists are divided on whether the central bank will act when it meets on Tuesday and Wednesday.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Hiring by the nation’s employers has slowed for four consecutive months__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), while retail sales contracted in May and new applications for jobless benefits have risen in five of the last six weeks.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ Within the Fed’s report on U.S. industry in May, the softness in the factory sector was widespread.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ Output for durable goods dropped 0.5 percent as auto production slid 1.5 percent. Production of nondurables fell 0.2 percent.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ Total industrial output, covering factories, mines and utilities, declined 0.1 percent. Analysts polled by Reuters had expected industrial production to rise 0.1 percent.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__¶ In a sign the factory sector’s weakness could continue into June, the__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) New York (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Federal__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Reserve Bank’s__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Empire State index fell to 2.3__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), a 15-point drop from the previous month and the lowest level since November 2011.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ That was far (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__below economists’ expectations of 13,__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) although the level still points to some growth.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ “(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__That is another indication that the U.S. economy is slowing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %),” said Justin Hoogendoorn, a fixed-income strategist at BMO Capital Markets in Chicago. “(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__It’s an ugly situatio__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__n__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).”

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
\\

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Specifically, strong manufacturing key to prevent a double dip ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**NYT 12**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (Floyd Norris - Floyd Norris is the chief financial correspondent of The New York Times and writes a weekly column for the financial section.Before joining The Times, Mr. Norris had been with Barron&amp;#39;s National Business and Financial Weekly since December 1982,)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(1/5/12 “Manufacturing Is Surprising Bright Spot in U.S. Economy” http:~/~/www.nytimes.com/2012/01/06/business/us-manufacturing-is-a-bright-spot-for-the-economy.html#h[IaeBih,1])

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ Since employment in the United States hit its recent low, in February 2010, the economy has added 2.4 million jobs through November, of which 302,000 were in manufacturing. With government payrolls shrinking, and financial services jobs also fewer, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing employment has played an important role in keeping the economy growing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). It also is helping that construction employment appears to have hit bottom. In the first 11 months of 2011, it is up a small amount.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ To be sure, the gains in manufacturing employment and exports have come after sharp declines during the recession and credit crisis. There are still 6 percent fewer manufacturing jobs than there were when President Obama took office at the beginning of 2009, and it seems very unlikely that he will be the first president since Bill Clinton, in his first term, to preside over growing manufacturing employment during a four-year term.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ During George W. Bush’s two terms, the number of manufacturing jobs fell by 17 percent in the first four years and by 12 percent in the following four years. The number declined by 1 percent in Mr. Clinton’s second term.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ The Institute for Supply Management survey of manufacturers has shown more companies planning to hire than to fire in every month since October 2009. That string of 27 months is the longest such string since 1972, but remains well behind the longest one, 36 months, which ended in December 1966.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ Over all, that survey has indicated that a plurality of companies has believed business is getting better for 29 consecutive months, and December’s reading of 53.9 was the strongest since June.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)¶ (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__This summer,__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) one widely watched part of the Institute for Supply Management survey showed that a small plurality of(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__companies reported new orders were falling, a fact that__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__helped to stimulate talk of a double-dip recession__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) But the latest reading, of 57.6, indicates widespread strength in new orders.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__¶ In an economy where there is widespread concern over consumer spending, and in which government spending__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) and payrolls (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__are under heavy pressure, manufacturing has become a bright spot. __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__It is not enough to produce a strong rebound, and __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__it remains vulnerable__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) to weakness overseas. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__But __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__it has helped to keep a weak economic recovery from turning into a new recession__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Strong manufacturing is Key to growth and a stable economy – jobs, innovation, trade deficits, resiliency ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Ettlinger and Gordon 11**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (Michael Ettlinger is the Vice President for Economic Policy at the Center for American Progress. Kate Gordon is the Vice President for Energy Policy at the Center for American Progress. )

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(April 2011. Center for American Progress “The Importance and Promise of American Manufacturing” http:~/~/www.americanprogress.org/wp-content/uploads/issues/2011/04/pdf/manufacturing.pdf)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__The health and future__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ of __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ in the U__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)nited (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__S__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)tates (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__matters__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). For starters, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__it __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__constitutes 12 percent of the U.S. economy__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). To put that in perspective, when the United States recently lost less than 4 percent of its gross domestic product, or national income, the result was labeled the “Great Recession.” Twelve percent of the economy matters a lot.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__But the __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ sector __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__also boasts an outsized importance__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) that is understated by even that 12 percent. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__One key reason__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) manufacturing is so important (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__is its position as the cornerstone of__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ the success of__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) many (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__other economically important activities__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). This role has been the subject of a longstanding debate as to whether the United States should hold onto its manufacturing sector or instead become a “postindustrial” society.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)This debate started in the 1980s when Japanese goods started flooding the U.S. market. Some economists argued then that America should move beyond competition for manufacturing jobs and settle instead into a new economic growth pattern based on service jobs in knowledge-based industries. These economists argued that just as the United States shifted away from agriculture and into industry, so should it shift from industry into services as the primary source of economic activity for the future.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)But this (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__“manufacturing versus services”__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) argument (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__set up a false dichotomy__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). A strong manufacturing sector does not come at the cost of a strong service sector— to the contrary, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__each manufacturing job__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) actually (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__supports multiple jobs in other sectors__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). As economists Stephen Cohen and John Zysman wrote in the late 1980s, the manufacturing sector does not just include the group of employees who work on the factory floor. Instead, the manufacturing sector has “direct linkages” to high-level service jobs throughout the economy: product and process engineering, design, operations and maintenance, transportation, testing, and lab work, as well as sector-specific payroll, accounting, and legal work.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Furthermore, “the more advanced or modern the production process, the longer and more complicated the chains or linkages,” note Cohen and Zysman in their 1988 book Manufacturing Matters: The Myth of the Post-Industrial Economy.1 If anything, the phenomenon Cohen and Zysman observed is even more evident today as manufacturing industries create many indirect jobs for each direct job created. Motor vehicle manufacturing, for example, now creates 8.6 indirect jobs for each direct job. Computer manufacturing creates 5.6 indirect jobs and steel product manufacturing creates 10.3 indirect jobs for each direct job.2

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)So manufacturing creates jobs, not just in the manufacturing sector but in a host of other occupations and industries. But that doesn’t settle the issue of the importance of having actual, physical manufacturing take place in the United States. The question remains, can manufacturing happen in, say, China, but still create associated high-quality service jobs here at home? __The answer is that it is, indeed, important__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ that the actual, physical manufacturing occur here. Made in America matters__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__When__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) shop floor (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing jobs depart, other jobs __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__go__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ with them—and __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__with those jobs goes the ability__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__to__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) create and (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__innovate__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__. Declines in__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) the U.S. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) sector (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__mean declines in our nation’s overall “industrial commons”—a set of related industries__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) and activities (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__including__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) those in (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__the__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) highly prized (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__knowledge based economy__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). According to Harvard economist Gary Pisano, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__when manufacturing moves overseas__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) so does this industrial commons, meaning that (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__we lose__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) not only production prowess but also the process (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__innovation__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__that comes from__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) colocating (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__research and development, design, engineering, and manufacturing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color:#000000;&amp;#34; %)“(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)In addition to undermining the ability of the United States to manufacture hightech products, the erosion of the industrial commons has seriously damaged the country’s ability to invent new ones,” writes Pisano in a recent Harvard Business Journal online debate.3 With the loss of the commons and the jobs comes a decline in U.S. workforce skills and the ability to invent and innovate that can only come from the hands-on experience of working in an industry.4

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)The upshot: (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__If we lose our ability to make things, we__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) may well (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__lose our ability to invent them__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)There is strong anecdotal evidence that if we cede production on a process invented in the United States then we may lose future iterations of innovation of that process. Solar panels are one example. Invented in New Jersey at Bell Laboratories in 1954, the production of solar photovoltaic panels has largely moved overseas (China is currently the world’s largest producer), and most new innovations in panel production, such as process improvements that make the panels far more powerful by altering their electrical properties, are happening outside of our nation.5

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Interestingly, this is less true for nonpanel solar power innovations, such as the holographic solar applications pioneered by small startups in Arizona and New York, possibly because these new innovations are still cutting-edge and not yet in commercial production at any real scale.6 Once these technologies do scale up, however, they too may be produced and improved overseas.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)One industry where the spatial relationship between manufacturing and innovation is most clearly shown by empirical data is the optoelectronics industry, which includes products such as lasers and fiber-optic telecommunications. In a recent set of studies, Carnegie Mellon University engineering professor Erica Fuchs examined the impact of offshoring production on technological innovation. Her key finding: When optoelectronics companies offshored production of their original designs to, for instance, Asia, they tended to produce those initial designs cheaply and efficiently. When these firms then began work on new and improved designs, however, they tended to lose valuable time and knowledge if their operations were off shore.7

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Thus, moving manufacturing overseas impeded the companies’ ability to compete and keep at the forefront of design and production and to efficiently push forward new technologies.8 Inexorably, then, these companies will follow other manufacturers who have shifted design and innovation closer to their physical operations— witness the photovoltaic manufacturing industry.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Fuchs’s findings are critical not only to the question of why basing manufacturing in the United States matters but also to the analysis of what kinds of policies might best support the types of manufacturing that will ultimately put our nation in the best economic position. In the most simplistic terms, Fuchs’s research shows that when you’re talking about the United States, manufacturing does matter, but (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__advanced and cutting-edge manufacturing matters even more. When such manufacturing leaves, it takes__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ much more than __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)the factory floor (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__jobs__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)—as important as those may be—(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__it takes__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) technology, innovation, and (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__the next generation of products with it__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). The United States will clearly never again compete in the most low-wage, laborintensive areas of industrial production. But (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__when it comes to advanced manufac turing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) that dominates the 21st century, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__we must compete if we want to hold onto our role as global innovators and entrepreneurs__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Beyond innovation and competitiveness, basing (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) in the United States also (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__is important to our overall national and economic security__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). The most clear-cut example of this, of course, is the importance of being able to produce for the needs of our armed forces. The importance of domestic capabilities in defense manufacturing is obvious—one doesn’t want to be dependent on foreign suppliers in a time of conflict. Equally obvious is the importance of keeping innovations in military technology close to home.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)This is underscored by a list kept by the State Department known as the International Traffic in Arms Regulations, or ITAR, which designates the manufactured goods and services deemed to be “defense articles” and tightly controls their export and import.9 The list includes a range of items from firearms and nuclear weapons systems to less obvious items like energy conversion devices that are specifically designed for military application.10

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Beyond defense, however, manufacturing offers a greater degree of economic security. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__The__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) simple (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__existence of __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__the sector helps balance out other sectors to create a more stable economy overall__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)11 (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Had__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), for example, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing been a larger share of the economy at the time of the__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__recent __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__housing and financial__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__ crises, the fragility of those__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ two __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__sectors would not have been__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) quite (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__as devastating to the overall economy__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)12

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Indeed, when multilateral development banks such as the World Bank Group fund international projects in the developing world, they often point to the importance of a “diverse economy”—that is, an economy based on a wide range of profitable sectors, not just a few—as essential to sustained, broad-based economic growth. The same holds true for industrialized nations.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)This kind of analysis, however, is seldom done in the United States at the national level because we have had a diverse economy overall. Individual regions and states, however, can be significantly less diversified.13 For this reason, states often develop economic plans aimed at making their economies more diverse. For instance, former Michigan Gov. Jennifer Granholm specifically set out to diversify her state’s economy away from traditional auto manufacturing and into other sectors such as solar technology, wave power, and electric drive trains.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)This kind of economic development strategy is rarely tried at the national level, however, perhaps due to concerns about excess involvement of government in the operation of the economy. Still, research abroad and at the regional level in the United States makes clear that putting too many of our eggs in one sectoral basket is a bad bet for long-term stability.14 Manufacturing, like any sector, is affected by economywide events, but (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing’s internal diversity__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)—supplying consumer goods as well as industrial goods, serving both domestic and external markets—(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__gives it great potential resiliency in__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) addition to simply (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__adding one more leg for the broader economy to stand on__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Domestic manufacturing is also the key to more balanced trading relationships__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)— a fact recognized by President Obama when he challenged the country to double its level of exports. Of course, that growth in exports doesn’t have to all be manufactured goods—but in truth it will need to mostly be notwithstanding the recent growth in services exports.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)That growth in services exports receives a lot of the attention but it is to some degree misplaced. A good deal of that increase is actually a byproduct of the outsourcing of manufacturing overseas. For instance, when a U.S. company sets up a foreign subsidiary to manufacture in another country, its U.S. parent may charge the foreign subsidiary for royalties, licensing fees, accounting, and engineering services. These transactions can be counted as U.S. exports of services and, in fact, appear to explain a large portion of the increase in U.S. exports of services.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Yet these of course do not represent an increase in overall U.S. production—the activities are servicing the same manufacturing they always did—it’s just that the manufacturing itself has moved overseas. Hardly a plus for the country, especially given the increasing trend for these associated services to eventually follow on the heels of the manufacturing activities they support.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)There also are inherent limitations in the export of services. Certainly bankers in New York can lend to firms in Tokyo, engineering consultants can advise clients in Frankfurt, and U.S. architects can design buildings in São Paulo. But that will always be the exception, not the rule. A Japanese borrower will generally first look to a Japanese lender, a European industrialist to a local engineering firm, and a South American real estate developer to a South American architect.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)With manufactured goods it’s about the good itself, not the language or the culture or other aspect of a service relationship. While some areas of service exports can grow—and their promotion is certainly to be encouraged—manufacturing is where our export growth is going to have to come from. The bottom line: Without a robust manufacturing sector, the U.S. balance of payments will deteriorate and the exodus of our national savings and earnings will slowly sap our economic strength.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Finally, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing matters for people. __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__One-tenth of all jobs__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ in the United States __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__are in manufacturing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) and these pay on average 20 percent more than the national average.15 They pay decent wages to production workers, many of whom lack a four-year college degree but have technical or associate’s degrees in skills related to their manufacturing work. These middle-skill workers make up more than 60 percent of today’s workforce.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)And manufacturing matters not to just these workers but to all workers. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Without manufacturing the downward pressure on wages__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ throughout the economy __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__would increase, with negative consequences for__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ America’s __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__overall economic well-being__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)— to wages, to income equality, and to middle-class families.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)So manufacturing matters for America.16 It matters for our technological leadership, national security, economic security, economic stability, national wealth, and the well-being of the middle class that underpins our economic strength. It’s important, but is it too far gone to save? No. The good news is that (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__while manufacturing in the U__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)nited (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__S__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)tates (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__is under threat,__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) and faces serious challenges, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__it is by no means a__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) mere (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__relic__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) of the past. It is a vibrant, large sector of our economy—even if sometimes it’s hard to see that as manufacturing jobs are lost, as factories close, and as sections of the country deindustrialize. To this we now turn.

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== SMRs create direct and indirect manufacturing jobs – they create more than any other reactor ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Locatelli and Mancini 10 **(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(Giorgio Locatelli and Mauro Mancini - Politecnico di Milano, Dept. Management, Economics and Industrial Engineering)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(11/13/10 “The role of the reactor size for an investment in the nuclear sector: An evaluation of not-financial parameters” http:~/~/www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0149197010001575)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)11. Impact on employment

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)This aspect is important especially for a public investor because welfare of the country is an important objective of his mission. However, a private investor will be interested to the government’s support following a higher number of new jobs created. This issue is so relevant that (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__the literature is rich of frameworks for the evaluation of new jobs created from new NPP programs__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) ( [U.S. DOE, 2005], [Oxford Economics, 2008], [INEEL, 2004], [Klinger et al., 2009] and [Bechtel Power Corporation et al., 2004]). The following considerations summarise their contribution with respect to the construction and the operation phases.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)11.1. Construction phase

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__There are three different impacts on employment__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %):

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__1. __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Direct. People employed in the __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__manufacturing of__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) components and (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__modules__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), on-site construction and operation of NPP.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)2. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Indirect. Jobs created in the extended nuclear supply chain: suppliers of equipment__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ manufacturers__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), suppliers of machineries and building materials, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__agencies for inspection and__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__safety__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ controls__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)3. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__Induced. Jobs created in non-nuclear industries due to the new jobs added __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__in the previous categories__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). They are the sum of non-nuclear jobs that would be created because of industry growth, such as additional grocery store employees, school teachers and residential construction workers. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__These jobs have a significant impact__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ especially __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__in local economies__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), as reported in ( [Wendling and Bezdek, 2006], [Nuclear Energy Institute, 2004] and [Nuclear Energy Institute, 2006]).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__The differential impact on new jobs creation is evaluated considering the comparison between an LR and four SMRs in the same site__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Oxford’s study (Oxford Economics, 2008) used Input–Output analysis to define the relationships between different kinds of impact through the use of multipliers, as in Fig. 4. We extrapolated direct on-site and off-site man years required for the construction of a 1340 MWe reactor from ( [U.S. DOE, 2005] and [Oxford Economics, 2008]). For what concern SMRs, the values of the two direct impacts were obtained from LRs’ values through the application of labour and equipment coefficients in Garrone et al. (2009). Indirect and induced impacts were obtained from the applications of multipliers.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Impact on construction employment is strongly differential and promotes the SMR choice__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %):

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)1. The (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__SMRs__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ in co-siting configuration __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__create 11% more__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ man years content __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__than LRs__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__. Major part of new jobs opportunities created by SMRs are related to__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) the major percentage of work content transferred off-site, through (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__modularization and pre-fabrication approaches__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %). __Multipliers indicate that off-site direct employment drives greater__ indirect and induced __effects than on-site__ direct employment. So, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__SMRs create a more beneficial impact t__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__hanks to the higher work content of facilities__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) and the following induced effects. Moreover, this welfare benefit does not undermine attractiveness of the investment.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)2. The amount of on-site employment is in Fig. 5. The phased demand for LR is from Oxford Economics (2008). We re-arranged the approach to three-years-construction SMRs to obtain a plausible schedule.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)The literature (Thomas et al., 2009) shows that one of the biggest challenges is finding qualified people, including craft labourers and technicians (qualified boilermakers, pipefitters, electricians, ironworkers), to support construction. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__SMRs’ demand is more time-levelled, therefore it will be easier to face the shortage of qualified construction workers__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), even if the total number of man years is higher than LR.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)11.2. Operation phase

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Positions in this phase include permanent plant operators and engineers, managers, accountants and general staffs. Extrapolation from existing plants’ experience (IAEA, 2001) shows average staffing levels of approximately one person per MW(e) for a single unit LR. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__For SMRs, the specific staffing level tends to increase to about 1.5 person/MWe__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)But existing SMRs are only scale models of LR designs. New GEN III+ SMRs incorporate features that require fewer personnel to operate and maintain the plant in a safe and reliable manner. Model presented in Garrone et al. (2009) concludes that a site with four 335 MWe SMRs has an OandM cost 24% higher than a site with one 1340 MWe LR. Labour cost is about the 70% of total OandM costs, so operational work content will experience roughly the same increase.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Concluding:

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color:#000000;&amp;#34; %)• (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)SMRs create a higher number of new jobs also in the operation phase;

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color:#000000;&amp;#34; %)• (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)new operation positions still involve indirect and induced impacts: SMRs and LRs are characterized by equal multipliers (Oxford Economics, 2008), but they amplify the higher direct operation employment of the SMR. Impact on operation employment is differential and promotes the SMR choice.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
==== SMRs revive domestic manufacturing – they will become a fulcrum for export growth ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Rosner and Goldberg 11**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (Robert Rosner, Professor, Departments of Astronomy and Astrophysics, and Physics, and the College; Senior Fellow @ UChicago. Stephen M. Goldberg is Special Assistant to the Director at Argonne National Laboratory)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(November 2011. Energy Policy Institute at Chicago The Harris School of Public Policy Studies “Small Modular Reactors – Key to Future Nuclear Power Generation in the U.S.” https:~/~/epic.sites.uchicago.edu/sites/epic.uchicago.edu/files/uploads/EPICSMRWhitePaperFinalcopy.pdf)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)As stated earlier, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__SMRs have the potential to__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) achieve significant greenhouse gas emission reductions. They could (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__provide__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) alternative (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__baseload__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) power generation (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__to facilitate the retirement of older__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), smaller, and less efficient coal generation (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__plants__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) that would, otherwise, not be good candidates for retrofitting carbon capture and storage technology. They could be deployed in regions of the U.S. and the world that have less potential for other forms of carbon-free electricity, such as solar or wind energy. There may be technical or market constraints, such as projected electricity demand growth and transmission capacity, which would support SMR deployment but not GW-scale LWRs. From the on-shore manufacturing perspective, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__a key point is that the manufacturing base needed for SMRs can be developed domestically.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) Thus, while the large commercial LWR industry is seeking to transplant portions of its supply chain from current foreign sources to the U.S., (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__the SMR industry offers the potential to establish a large domestic manufacturing base building upon already existing__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)U.S. manufacturing (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__infrastructure and capability__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), including the Naval shipbuilding and underutilized domestic nuclear component and equipment plants. The study team learned that (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__a number of sustainable domestic jobs could be created__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %) –(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) that is, the full panoply of design, manufacturing, supplier, and construction activities – (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__if the U.S. can establish itself as a credible__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) and substantial (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__designer__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif;