 Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ viable U.S.-centric SMR industry would enable the U.S. to recapture technological leadership in commercial nuclear technology, which has been lost to suppliers in France, Japan, Korea, Russia,__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) and, now rapidly emerging, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__China__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %).

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Scenario 2 is volatility ====

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== The US is increasingly dependent on natural gas - it’s inherently volatile, killing the economy ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Huber 12**

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Lisa Huber, Rocky Mountain Institute Intern, 8/1/12, “Managing Natural Gas Volatility: The Answer is Blowin’ in the Wind,” http:~/~/blog.rmi.org/blog_Managing_Natural_Gas_Volatility_The_Answer_is_Blowin_in_the_wind

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
The recent shale gas boom has gained the reputation as our energy savior: clean, domestic, cheap, and plentiful. But, the attractiveness of today’s (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__low natural gas price can cause us to overlook a serious risk: volatility__(%%)__. Natural (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)gas is one of the riskiest commodities(%%) around, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)historically bearing twice the volatility(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %) (%%)__price risk (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__of oil__(%%). While this is common knowledge among industry professionals and commodity traders, the long-term risk often goes ignored, despite previous attempts to put a price tag on volatility. Why This Matters According to RMI Chief Scientist Amory Lovins, “we must not set our sights too low and end up with a 20-year plan instead of a 21st century goal.” This logic on the importance of long-term strategy is the driving force behind RMI’s Reinventing Fire, a vision and roadmap for a 150 percent bigger 2050 U.S. economy requiring no oil, coal, or nuclear energy, and one-third less natural gas. Without accounting for the volatility risk of natural gas, wholesale power-producing renewables don’t appear very competitive without the support of tax credits (expiring at the end of the year for wind) and renewable portfolio standards, whose incentives are less substantial than in the recent past. Investing in gas over wind without consideration of volatility would be like chasing yield without regard to risk—something a prudent investor would never dream of. (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__As__(%%)__ U.S. (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)natural gas supply grows(%%)__ and liquefied natural gas export terminals come online, (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__our economy becomes more__(%%) and more (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__dependent on__(%%)__ the success of shale; (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)changes in natural gas prices could greatly impact the broader market(%%)__. Historically speaking, __natural gas tends to move opposite the market__ (that’s a negative beta for the finance geeks out there). __As (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)natural gas prices rise and the market falls(%%)__ (remember 2008?), (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__consumers take a significant hit__(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Energy price volatility hurts the economy – it affects all consumers and businesses ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**EIA 01**

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Energy Information Administration 4/10/01, http:~/~/www.eia.gov/oiaf/economy/energy_price.html

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
__Volatility matters for all consumers and producers__ in the economy. Business__ firms, both energy and non-energy, make investment decisions based on expectations about prices__. If decisions are made on the expectation of low (or high) energy prices, and the energy market varies sharply from these expectations, firms may make inappropriate investment and business decisions. Even those __firms that expect volatility may be adversely affected by__ simply __putting off a decision until the market is more stable__. __Consumer purchases__ __of housing__ and consumer durables such as __autos and appliances are__ also __affected by instability in energy markets__. The economy would most likely perform better with stable or predictable energy prices, than when the price of energy fluctuates greatly.

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Nuclear is key to reduce energy price volatility – it helps every sector ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**EU Department of Energy and Climate Change 12**

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
EU Department of Energy and Climate Change 5/18/12, “Davey: Climate change policies could halve negative impacts of energy price shocks,” [[http:~~/~~/www.decc.gov.uk/en/content/cms/news/pn12_061/pn12_061.aspx&amp;#62;&amp;#62;url:http://www.decc.gov.uk/en/content/cms/news/pn12_061/pn12_061.aspx]]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
“(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__The more we can shift to alternative fuels__(%%), and use energy efficiently, (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__the more we can ensure that our economy does not become hostage to__(%%) far-flung events and to (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__the volatility of market forces__(%%)” (Edward Davey) (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__The negative impact that spikes in__(%%) global __oil, gas and coal (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)prices(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)have(%%)__ on the UK (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__could be reduced by over 50%__(%%) in 2050 as a result of climate change policies, Edward Davey said today. The analysis, produced by Oxford Economics and commissioned by Government, shows how the UK’s sensitivity to oil and gas price shocks could be reduced by (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__using__(%%) low-carbon forms of electricity generation including renewables, (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__new nuclear__(%%) and through increasing energy efficiency. Secretary of State, Edward Davey said: “(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__Every step__(%%) the UK takes (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__toward__s(%%) building (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__a low-carbon economy reduces our dependency on__(%%) fossil fuels, and on (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__volatile__(%%) global (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__energy prices__(%%). “Only last year, the impact of the Arab Spring on wholesale gas prices, pushed up UK household bills by 20%. “The more we can shift to alternative fuels, and use energy efficiently, the more we can ensure that our economy does not become hostage to far-flung events and to the volatility of market forces. “Of course, there are costs to building more low-carbon plant, but the gains are so much greater, and crucially they are lasting. “This is about building a more resilient economy and providing more stable energy prices for the generations that follow us”. Energy prices have been trending up over the past decade and are becoming increasingly volatile. Once the UK fully transitions to a low-carbon economy, (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__the negative impacts of__(%%)__ energy price (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)volatility on these 4 factors are halved(%%)__: Halving the impact of energy price volatility on disposable household income, and therefore (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__reducing amount households would have to put aside to spend on energy __(%%)__bills__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %). __Halving the __(%%)__negative (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)impact on(%%)__ the level of (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__business investment. Halving __(%%)__the impact on (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)inflation Halving (%%)the impact on levels of (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)unemployment, which could rise through(%%)__ increased (% style=&amp;#34;background: #ffff00&amp;#34; %)__economic inactivity caused by high energy prices__(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Specifically, SMRs solve market risk and fit the need to replace natural gas ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Rosner and Goldberg 11**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (Robert Rosner, Professor, Departments of Astronomy and Astrophysics, and Physics, and the College; Senior Fellow @ UChicago. Stephen M. Goldberg is Special Assistant to the Director at Argonne National Laboratory)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(November 2011. Energy Policy Institute at Chicago The Harris School of Public Policy Studies “Small Modular Reactors – Key to Future Nuclear Power Generation in the U.S.” https:~/~/epic.sites.uchicago.edu/sites/epic.uchicago.edu/files/uploads/EPICSMRWhitePaperFinalcopy.pdf)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Furthermore, CBO discussed the market risk associated with GW-scale plants: __Market risk is the component of risk that investors cannot protect themselves against by diversifying their portfolios__. Investors require compensation for market risk because investments exposed to such risk are more likely to have low returns when the economy as a whole is weak and resources are more highly valued…In the case of nuclear construction guarantees provided to investor-owned utilities or merchant power providers, for example, plant construction may be more likely to be slowed or canceled when the demand for electricity is depressed by a weak economy. 23,24

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__SMRs could potentially mitigate such a risk in several ways. First, __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__SMRs have lower precompletion risk due to shorter construction schedules__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (24-36 months as compared with 48 months). Second, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__because of their smaller size, SMRs have lower market risk because __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__there is significantly less power than needs to be sold__ as compared with GW-level plants. Finally, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__the modular nature of SMRs affords the flexibility to build capacity__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) on an (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__as-needed__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) basis. __In the case of unsubsidized financing,__ particularly relevant to merchant markets, utility (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__decision makers that have significant aversion to __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__risk of future __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__natural gas spikes__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (i.e., gas prices rising to about $7/Mcf or one standard deviation above the recent average behavior of natural gas prices) (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__would __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__possibly __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__view alternatives__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ to gas-fired generation __(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__as attractive options__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), particularly if the investment requirements are comparable – (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__SMRs could__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __potentially (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0); background: rgb(255, 255, 0)&amp;#34; %)__“fit the bill.”__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Economic collapse causes global nuclear war. ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Merlini, Senior Fellow – Brookings, 11**(%%) [Cesare Merlini, nonresident senior fellow at the Center on the United States and Europe and chairman of the Board of Trustees of the Italian Institute for International Affairs (IAI) in Rome. He served as IAI president from 1979 to 2001. Until 2009, he also occupied the position of executive vice chairman of the Council for the United States and Italy, which he co-founded in 1983. His areas of expertise include transatlantic relations, European integration and nuclear non-proliferation, with particular focus on nuclear science and technology. A Post-Secular World? DOI: 10.1080/00396338.2011.571015 Article Requests: Order Reprints : Request Permissions Published in: journal Survival, Volume 53, Issue 2 April 2011 , pages 117 - 130 Publication Frequency: 6 issues per year Download PDF Download PDF (~~357 KB) View Related Articles To cite this Article: Merlini, Cesare &amp;#39;A Post-Secular World?&amp;#39;, Survival, 53:2, 117 – 130]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.3in; margin-right: 0.3in; margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; widows: 0; orphans: 0&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)Two neatly opposed scenarios for the future of the world order illustrate the range of possibilities, albeit at the risk of oversimplification. (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__The first scenario entails the premature crumbling of the post-Westphalian system. One or more of the acute tensions apparent today evolves into an open and traditional conflict between states__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), perhaps even (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__involving the use of nuclear weapons. The crisis might be triggered by a collapse of the global economic and financial system, the vulnerability of which we have just experienced, and the prospect of a second Great Depression, with consequences for peace and democracy similar to those of the first.__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) Whatever the trigger, (% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__the unlimited exercise of national sovereignty, exclusive self-interest and rejection of outside interference would likely be amplified, emptying, perhaps entirely, the half-full glass of multilateralism__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %), including the UN and the European Union. Many of the more likely conflicts, such as between Israel and Iran or India and Pakistan, have potential religious dimensions. Short of war, tensions such as those related to immigration might become unbearable. Familiar issues of creed and identity could be exacerbated. One way or another, the secular rational approach would be sidestepped by a return to theocratic absolutes, competing or converging with secular absolutes such as unbridled nationalism.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
=== 1AC – Solvency ===

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Contention 3: Solvency ====

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Licensing is the biggest hurdle for small modular reactors or SMRs Now ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Wheeler 11**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (Brian Wheeler - Associate Editor of Power Engineering)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(February 11, “Small Modular Reactors Are &amp;#34;Hot&amp;#34;” proquest. Power Engineering. Volume 115. No. 2)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
The distant timeframe is for numerous reasons. The plan is to build a SMR, start generating power and bring more online to form a larger nuclear plant, as needed. The SMRs are expected to be ready, as the DOE calls it, to &amp;#34;plug and play&amp;#34; when the reactor arrives on-site. Sounds simple? There are still obstacles that need to be defeated before the arrival of a commercial SMR. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Licensing is the number one challenge at this point__(%%). The Nuclear Regulatory Commission established the Advanced Reactor Program in 2009 to focus on new licensing technologies. NRC is studying several pre-application reviews to identify possible technical issues, such as safety, security and emergency planning. The light water(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__small reactors may be very similar to large designs, but they still must go through a separate licensing process__(%%). Vendors that engage the NRC early can resolve these technical issues. To address safety and security concerns, the small reactors will be built with post-9/11 safety concepts into the designs. NRC expects the first application submission by 2012. The funds for the research and development of the SMR could pose a problem as well. But the Obama administration has requested $38.9 million for the 2011 fiscal year budget for the development of SMRs. The DOE supports public and private partnerships to advance mature SMR designs and supports &amp;#34;research and development activities to advance the understanding and demonstration of innovative reactor technologies and concepts.&amp;#34; Among other goals, in FY2011 the DOE plans to “solicit, select and award project(s) with industry partners for cost-sharing the U.S. NRC review of design certification document for up to two of the most promising light water SMR concept(s) for near-term licensing and deployment” and “develop recommendations, in collaboration with NRC and industry, for changes in NRC policy, regulations or guidance to license and enable SMRs for deployment in the U.S. And as the general public’s interest in energy continues to grow, so does the interest in SMRs, said Philip Moor, vice president of consulting and management firm High Bridge Associates. If approved, the funding towards the development of small reactors in the U.S. may play a part of the International Atomic Energy Agency’s estimate of between 49 to 97 SMRs built by 2030. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Utilities may have more interest in SMRs once the NRC gains more expertise and the uncertainty of deploying these__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__reactors__(%%) in the U.S. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__can be addressed__(%%). (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)And(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__ if the regulator approves any of the designs for licensing, the U.S. may see a stronger nuclear renaissance take place__(%%). As we have seen, some operators have scaled back or completely pulled out on plans to build new large reactors due to the cost. The ability to construct these reactors in factories could lead to lower costs and shorter construction times. Of course, the upfront capital to develop and engineer the facility is going to be needed. But after that, the reactors can be built in the controlled environment in repetition to lower cost, which could in return lead to more clean energy on the grid.

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Regulatory gridlock is blocking SMRs – streamlining regulations is key to commercialization – it’s modeled globally ====

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Jessica (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Lovering**(%%), Ted (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Nordhaus**(%%), (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**and**(%%) Michael (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**Shellenberger**(%%) are policy analyst, chairman, and president of the Breakthrough Institute, a public policy think tank and research organization, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:1.0em;&amp;#34; %)**9/7**(%%)/2012 (http:~/~/www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2012/09/07/out_of_the_nuclear_closet?page=full)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Nuclear has enjoyed bipartisan support in Congress for more than 60 years, but the enthusiasm is running out. The Obama administration deserves credit for authorizing funding for two small modular reactors, which will be built at the Savannah River site in South Carolina. But a much more sweeping reform of U.S. nuclear energy policy is required. At present,(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ the N__(%%)uclear (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__R__(%%)egulatory (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__C__(%%)ommission (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__has little institutional knowledge of anything other than light-water reactors and virtually no capability to review or regulate alternative designs. This affects nuclear innovation in other countries as well, since the NRC remains__(%%), despite its many critics, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__the global gold standard for__(%%) thorough(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ regulation__(%%) of nuclear energy(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__. **Most other countries follow the NRC&amp;#39;s lead when it comes to establishing new **__(%%)technical and operational(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__** standards for the design, construction, and operation of nuclear plants**__(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__What&amp;#39;s needed__(%%) now (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__is a__(%%) new national (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__commitment to the__(%%) development, testing, demonstration, and early stage (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__commercialization of__(%%) a broad range of new nuclear technologies ~-~- from much smaller light-water reactors to next generation ones ~-~- in search of a few (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__designs that can be mass produced and deployed at a significantly lower cost__(%%) than current designs. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__This will require __(%%)both greater public support for nuclear innovation and(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ an entirely different regulatory framework__(%%) to review and approve new commercial designs.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
In the meantime, developing countries will continue to build traditional, large nuclear power plants. But (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__time is of the essence__(%%). With the lion&amp;#39;s share of future carbon emissions coming from those emerging economic powerhouses, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__the need to develop smaller and cheaper designs that can scale faster is all the more important__(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== Streamlining bureaucratic licensing transforms the nuclear industry – the market is strong enough to support SMRs. ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Spencer 11**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (Jack Spencer is Research Fellow in Nuclear Energy in the Thomas A. Roe Institute for Economic Policy Studies)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(2/15/11 “Is the President’s Small Reactor Push the Right Approach?” http:~/~/blog.heritage.org/2011/02/15/is-the-presidents-small-reactor-push-the-right-approach/)

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Establishing a Regulatory Framework

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
The Obama budget essentially acknowledged the regulatory problem in his budget, which requests $67 million for DOE to work on licensing technical support for small light water reactors. While the intent is correct, the approach is wrong. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__The Administration is relying on the same bureaucratic, taxpayer-funded process that is stifling large reactor certification__(%%) when it should use this opportunity to establish a new, more efficient licensing pathway.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Instead of paying for DOE bureaucrats to get in the way of commercial progress, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__the Administration should commit to ensuring__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(%%)that(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__the__(%%) U.S.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__N__(%%)uclear (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__R__(%%)egulatory (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__C__(%%)ommission (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__is fully equipped__(%%) and prepared(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__to regulate new__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(%%)reactor designs. This should include high-temperature gas-cooled reactors and liquid-metal-cooled fast reactors as well as (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__small light water designs. This would provide a strong regulatory foundation for__(%%) each of the expected (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__design certification applications__(%%). The DOE should have no role in the process. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__If a company wants to get its reactor design certified__(%%) for commercial use in the U.S., (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__it should be able to go straight to the NRC__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)for that service(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Such an approach would substantially decrease the risk associated with getting designs certified, which__(%%) in turn (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__would alleviate the need for public support__(%%). Then, instead of seeking taxpayer funds to offset regulatory risk, reactor designers could develop investors to support the certification process.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Build the Framework and They Will Come

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Nuclear energy is already clean, safe, and affordable.(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Introducing small reactors could make it transformatio__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__nal__(%%). But the federal government should not drive the process. It should be supported by the market. If the underlying technology is as strong as many of us believe it to be, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__the federal government needs only to provide a predictable, stable, efficient, and fair regulatory environment__(%%). The rest will happen on its own—or it won’t.

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== SMRs rejuvenate the nuclear industry by resolving financing challenges. ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Davenport 12**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) [Coral, energy and environment correspondent – The National Journal, Cleaner Energy, Beyond the Horizon April 19, 2012 The National Journal, Lexis]

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
However, many of the nation&amp;#39;s nuclear power reactors will reach retirement age in the coming decades, and there are no plans to replace them. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__The biggest challenge__(%%) in building a nuclear-power plant (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__is financing: It can take up to $10 billion and six years to build a plant__(%%), compared with less than half that time and cost to build a natural-gas facility. Some of that cost is for construction, and some of it is for higher rates of insurance and liability in the wake of the Fukushima nuclear disaster in Japan. Either way, the nuclear-power industry says that (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Wall Street isn&amp;#39;t interested in investing in new plants__(%%), and the result is a freeze on getting this major source of new zero-carbon power onto the electric grid for the foreseeable future. But what if a nuclear-power plant wasn&amp;#39;t so expensive to build?(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ Small modular reactors might solve that problem.__(%%) Companies such as Northrup Grumman and Babcock and Wilcox have developed plans to mass-produce small, identical modular nuclear reactors that could be built for a fraction of the cost of existing plants. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__Two main factors drive the cost of a nuclear__(%%) power (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__plant: size and on-site construction.__(%%) A typical nuclear power plant is massive and produces enough electricity to power a city (about 1 million homes). (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__On-site construction__(%%) of such a project (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__requires billions of dollars__(%%), reams of paperwork, and years of regulatory hurdles. So (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__engineers have designed __(%%)nuclear (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__plants that__(%%) are one-third the size of a typical plant and(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ can be cheaply mass-produced and delivered__(%%) to various sitesmuch like the savings on prefabricated houses. Mass-producing small plants would cut down on the price and make low-carbon nuclear power available to rural communities that can&amp;#39;t consider it otherwise. Electric utilities could customize the size of the plants, ordering multiple reactors and getting a discount for a two-pack, four-pack, or six-pack of identical reactors that would work together. Or(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ a power company could__(%%) just (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__order premade plug-and-play reactors__(%%) as its service population grows. The(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ modular reactor designs include__(%%) key improvements over older nuclear plants: They have(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ advanced safety systems__(%%), (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__allowing__(%%) them to operate for up to three days in the case of power outage and thus offer better (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__prevention against__(%%) a Fukushima-style (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__meltdowns__(%%);(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ they also will be able to burn and reuse parts of the spent __(%%)nuclear (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__fuel, cutting down on nuclear waste__(%%). For now, however, these designs remain on the drawing board. To get a small modular plant plugged into the grid, a utility will first have to pay up to $500 million for the design to be approved and permitted by the Nuclear Regulatory Commissionabout a five-year process.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0.14in; line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)
\\

(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;page-break-before: always&amp;#34; %)
==== Cheap natural gas won’t block SMR commercialization ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Marston 12**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (Theodore U. Marston PHD. – Principal @ Marston Consulting. Board of Managers, Idaho National Laboratory. Formerly DOE NERAC Generation IV Oversight Committee 2001-2002)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(March 2012, “Status of Small Modular Light Water Reactors in the US” in “The Nuclear Decarbonization Option: Profiles of Selected Advanced Reactor Technologies”

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
The primary economic challenge to the commercialization of smLWRs is whether the electricity production costs are (1) affordable and (2) competitive with other forms of generation. With regard to affordability, smLWRs offer potential optionality to the US electric utilities, when the only real options for large generation additions are gas fired, coal fired or large nuclear plants. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__SmLWRs__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__,__(%%) being smaller and modular, potentially offer a more manageable nuclear option. SmLWRs (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__are more ‘affordable’__(%%), i.e. less of a fiscal risk. They can be deployed in much smaller increments, matching the utilities’ load growths better and reduce the ‘single shaft’ generation risk to an acceptable level.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Competing with other forms of electricity generation is a much greater challenge today. Vast amounts of natural gas are being discovered across the US in so-called tight gas (shale) deposits, resulting in cheap and abundant natural gas. The current spot market price of natural gas is less than $3.00/MMBTU. Carbon restraints (taxes or credits), which would improve the competitiveness of smLWRs, appear unlikely to arise in the near future. However (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__it is expected that carbon emissions from large stationary sources will be reduced systematically__(%%) over time one way or another, and US (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__utilities are very interested in reducing their ‘carbon footprints__(%%)’. If the economics of the smLWRs are what some of the designs claim, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__there is a real chance to compete with natural gas__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(%%)fired plants, (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__particularly when__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__ carbon constraints are in place__(%%). The cost competitiveness of smLWR depend heavily on achieving the following opportunities:

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
l Streamline design and manufacturing are necessary to offset the economies of scale of other generation options, particularly nuclear plants. ALWRs are becoming larger and larger due to the economies of scale. The only prospect to reverse this effect for the smaller smLWRs is to streamline the shop fabrication of the NSSS and other modules, ship them to the site and install them rapidly. The requisite quality standards must be maintained throughout the entire process.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
l Modularity of the smLWRs provides the opportunity to transform how we design, build, operate and decommission nuclear power plants.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
l Reduce construction time by modularization and construction efficiencies

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
l (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__SMRs do not require loan guarantees. This sets the smLWR apart from the larger ALWR__(%%), which currently benefit from federal loan guarantees, especially for regulated utilities. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__Experience shows the loan guarantee process to be a protracted and expensive affair, requiring the expenditure of significant political and fiscal capital.__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% class=&amp;#34;western&amp;#34; %)
==== And, SMRs are super safe – accidents, attack, disasters ====

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; font-size: 1em&amp;#34; %)**Rosner and Goldberg 11**(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %) (Robert Rosner, Professor, Departments of Astronomy and Astrophysics, and Physics, and the College; Senior Fellow @ UChicago. Stephen M. Goldberg is Special Assistant to the Director at Argonne National Laboratory)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)(November 2011. Energy Policy Institute at Chicago The Harris School of Public Policy Studies “Small Modular Reactors – Key to Future Nuclear Power Generation in the U.S.” https:~/~/epic.sites.uchicago.edu/sites/epic.uchicago.edu/files/uploads/EPICSMRWhitePaperFinalcopy.pdf)

(% align=&amp;#34;JUSTIFY&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%; &amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
While the focus in this paper is on the business case for SMRs, the safety case also is an important element of the case for SMRs. Although SMRs (the designs addressed in this paper) use the same fuel type and the same light water cooling as gigawatt (GW)-scale light water reactors (LWRs), (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__there are significant enhancements in__(%%) the reactor(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__design that contribute to__(%%) the upgraded (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__safety__(%%) case. Appendix A provides a brief overview of the various technology options for SMRs, including the light water SMR designs that are the focus of the present analysis.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
Light water (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__SMR__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__ designs__(%%) proposed to date (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__incorporate passive safety features that utilize gravity-driven__(%%) or natural convection(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__systems__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %) – (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__rather than__(%%) engineered, (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__pump-driven systems – to supply backup cooling__(%%) in unusual circumstances. (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__These__(%%) passive systems should (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)also(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__ minimize the need for prompt operator actions__(%%) in any upset condition. The designs rely on natural circulation for both normal operations and accident conditions, requiring no primary system pumps. In addition, these SMR designs utilize integral designs, meaning(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__all major__(%%) primary (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__components are located in a single, high-strength pressure vessel.__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %) __That feature is expected to result in__(%%) a much (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__lower susceptibility to__(%%) certain potential events, such as a(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__loss of coolant__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(%%)accident, because there is no large external primary piping. In addition, light water SMRs would have a much lower level of decay heat than large plants and, therefore, would require less cooling after reactor shutdown. Specifically, in a post-Fukushima lessons-learned environment, the study team believes that the current (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__SMR designs have__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %) (%%)three(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__inherent advantages over__(%%) the (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__current__(%%) class of large operating (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__reactors__(%%), namely:

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
~1. These (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__designs__(%%) mitigate and, potentially, (% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %)__eliminate the__(% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__ need for back-up__(%%) or emergency electrical (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__generators__(%%), relying exclusively on robust battery power to maintain minimal safety operations.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
2. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__They improve seismic capability with__(%%) the containment and (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__reactor vessels__(%%) in a pool of water (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__underground__(%%); this dampens the effects of any earth movement and greatly enhances the ability of the system to withstand earthquakes.

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-left: 0.2in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
3. (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__They provide__(% style=&amp;#34;background: #00ffff&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__large__(%%) and robust (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__underground pool storage__(%%) for the spent fuel, drastically (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__reducing the potential of uncovering__(%%) of these (% style=&amp;#34;font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 0.8em; background: rgb(0, 255, 255)&amp;#34; %)__pools__(%%).

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0.14in; line-height: 115%&amp;#34; %)
\\</headline></objectSummary></objects>